 => when we submit a query , oracle uses following methods to locate the record

    1  TABLE SCAN
    2  INDEX SCAN

 => in "TABLE SCAN"  oracle scans complete table i.e. each and every row.

=> in " INDEX SCAN "  on avg oracle scans half of the table , so index scan is faster than
     table scan.

                  SELECT * FROM emp WHERE sal = 3000 ;     (index scan)
                  SELECT * FROM emp WHERE sal >= 3000;    (index scan)
                  SELECT * FROM emp WHERE sal <= 3000;    (index scan)

                  SELECT * FROM emp WHERE  ename='BLAKE' ;    (table scan)
                  SELECT * FROM emp ;                                              (table scan)
 
 UNIQUE index :-
 ==============

   => a unique index doesn't allow duplicate values into the column on which index is created 

                CREATE UNIQUE INDEX  I2 ON EMP(ename) ; 

			   K

	       G                                                      Q

 ADAMS  *                JAMES *              MARTIN *              SCOTT *
 ALLEN   *                JONES *              MILLER *               SMITH *
 BLAKE   *

  SELECT * FROM emp WHERE ename='BLAKE' ;      (index scan)
  
  INSERT INTO emp(empno,ename,sal) VALUES(100,'BLAKE',2000);  => ERROR

  what are the different methods to enforce uniqueness ?

 
    1  declare  primary key / unique constraint
    2  create unique index 

 NOTE :- 

  => primary key / unique columns are automatically indexed by oracle.

  => oracle creates unique index on primary key & unique columns 
       and unique index doesn't allow duplicates , so primary key / unique also doesn't
       allow duplicates.

                   primary key   =   unique index  + not null
                   unique          =    unique index 

  
  USER_INDEXES :- 
  --------------------------

   => stores indexes created by user

    display list of indexes and type created on emp table ?

    SELECT INDEX_NAME,INDEX_TYPE
    FROM USER_INDEXES
    WHERE TABLE_NAME='EMP' ; 

   display index names and column names ?

    SELECT INDEX_NAME,COLUMN_NAME
    FROM USER_IND_COLUMNS
    WHERE TABLE_NAME='EMP' ;
 
  => DISPLAY   index name    column name    index type  ?

   SELECT  T1.INDEX_NAME,T2.COLUMN_NAME,T1.INDEX_TYPE
   FROM USER_INDEXES T1
   INNER JOIN USER_IND_COLUMNS T2
   ON T1.INDEX_NAME = T2.INDEX_NAME
   WHERE T1.TABLE_NAME='EMP' ; 

